########################################################################

###########################
##  Initialization

DOCUMENT();

loadMacros(
"PGstandard.pl",
"MathObjects.pl",
"AnswerFormatHelp.pl",
"PGcourse.pl",
);

TEXT(beginproblem());


###########################
#  Setup

Context("Numeric");

$a = non_zero_random(2,5,1);
$b = $a + non_zero_random(1,4,1);
$c = $b + non_zero_random(1,4,1);

$answer1 = Compute("$b");
$answer2 = Compute("$c");

$steadystate = Compute("($c-$b) x + $b")->reduce();

############################
##  Main text

Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT
Consider the equation \( u_t = $a u_{xx} \), \( 0 < x < 1 \), \( t > 0 \).
The boundary values were kept at constant temperatures.
Suppose that the steady state solution turns out to be $steadystate .
$BR
What were the boundary values?
$BR
\( u(0,t) = \) \{ ans_rule(20) \}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("numbers") \}
$BR
\( u(1,t) = \) \{ ans_rule(20) \}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("numbers") \}
END_TEXT
Context()->normalStrings;


#############################
##  Answer evaluation

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

ANS( $answer1->cmp() );
ANS( $answer2->cmp() );

#############################
##  Solution

Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_SOLUTION

We evaluate the steady state at \( x = 0 \) and \( x = 1 \),
to obtain that 
\( u(0,t) = $b \) and
\( u(1,t) = $c \).
END_SOLUTION
Context()->normalStrings;

;

ENDDOCUMENT();
